Royals was selected by the Chiefs in the fourth round of April's draft. He has an average frame but moves well, as shown by a solid 4.42 40, which included a class-best 1.49 10-yard split. He's a perimeter receiver who primarily works in the short area and lived on hook routes at Utah State. Even in a good Chiefs offense, Royals is a long shot for 2025 fantasy value, as he'll be behind Xavier Worthy, Rashee Rice, Hollywood Brown and perhaps JuJu Smith-Schuster on the depth chart. He's only worth drafting in dynasty.

Wicks is entering his third NFL season after catching exactly 39 passes during each of his first two years in Green Bay. He's generally been a depth receiver, but there were seven games last season in which he played at least 70% of the offensive snaps (Romeo Doubs and/or Christian Watson were sidelined those weeks). Wicks handled a healthy 22% target share (6.6 per game), but wasn't overly productive. After a strong 5-78-2 showing on 13 targets (24.8 fantasy points) in Week 4, he failed to clear seven targets, five receptions, 49 yards or 9.9 fantasy points in any of the other six outings. Even with Christian Watson likely to miss all or most of 2025, Wicks will have his hands full finding reps with Matthew Golden, Doubs, Jayden Reed and Savion Williams also on the roster. Wicks isn't worth drafting.

Williams was selected by Green Bay in the third round of April's draft. He is the heaviest WR in this class (222 pounds), has big hands (10.3 inches) and plays mostly on the perimeter (82% of routes), but he's a short-range target, as shown by his 6.4 aDOT (second lowest in this WR class) and 10.2 YPR (lowest) last season. In addition to his 87 targets, Williams posted a 51-322-6 rushing line in 2024. He ran a strong 4.48 40 and has the potential to emerge as a multi-faceted (rusher, receiver, returner) asset in the pros. Williams' path to consistent targets in 2025 is tricky, as Romeo Doubs, Jayden Reed and fellow rookie Matthew Golden headline the depth chart. He's only worth a late-round flier, but is a good dynasty hold.

Helm was selected by the Titans in the fourth round of April's draft. His career 80% catch rate is best in this class (min. 25 targets), but he wasn't used a ton (99 targets and a 6% share in 55 games) in a good Texas offense. He underwhelmed at the combine, running a 4.84 40 at 241 pounds and posting a class-low 30-inch vertical. Helm will battle Josh Whyle for backup duties behind Chig Okonkwo, and is not a short-term fantasy option.
No outlook available.

Smith was selected by the Jets in the fourth round of April's draft. The Georgia product was limited to a class-low 5.5% of the targets during his 47 games with the Bulldogs. He dropped nine of his 76 targets last season, though his career 16.0 aDOT tops this class. Smith is a long shot for consistent fantasy value in the Jets' low-volume passing game, but he has a path to snaps with Allen Lazard, Josh Reynolds and Malachi Corley as his top competition behind Garrett Wilson.

TeSlaa was selected by Detroit in the third round of April's draft. He is the only WR in this class who had zero recorded drops during his Division I tenure, though his 1.48 YPRR while at Arkansas is lowest among all WRs in this rookie class. He showed well at the combine, though, including a 4.43 40 at 214 pounds. TeSlaa will operate as a depth receiver behind Amon-Ra St. Brown, Jameson Williams and perhaps Tim Patrick and Kalif Raymond this season. He's only worth rostering in dynasty.

Martinez was selected by the Seahawks in the seventh round of April's draft. The Miami product is a big, power back who is effective as a rusher -- his 4.48 YAC last season trailed only Ashton Jeanty, and the same goes for his 3.88 career rate -- but he may not do much as a receiver in the pros. Martinez will begin his career buried behind Kenneth Walker III and Zach Charbonnet, so he's well off the fantasy radar.

Evans was selected by the Panthers in the fifth round of April's draft. He is a capable two-way tight end who peaked as a receiver with a 43-421-3 receiving line in 2024 at Notre Dame. It was a solid rebound after substantial missed action in 2022 (broken foot) and 2023 (torn ACL). Evans ran a solid 4.74 40-yard dash at 258 pounds at the combine. He'll likely slot in as the team's No. 3 tight end behind second-year Ja'Tavion Sanders and veteran Tommy Tremble.

Hawes was selected by the Bills in the fifth round of April's draft. He did a lot of blocking and produced only a 16-195-0 receiving line in 12 games (5% target share) last season, his lone campaign at Georgia Tech. He's unlikely to emerge as a consistent pass catcher in the pros.

Ouzts was selected by the Seahawks in the fifth round of April's draft. The heaviest FB/TE in this class (274 pounds), Ouzts primarily worked as a blocker and his 3% target share last season limited him to 108 yards on 10 targets. He's unlikely to ever see enough targets to find his way to fantasy relevance, especially considering he's expected to focus on fullback duties in Seattle.

draftedPlayers.outlook_2025: The reigning No. 1 fantasy receiver, Chase outscored second-place Justin Jefferson by a massive 85.5 points. His career year included nine top-10 fantasy weeks (three more than any other receiver), as well as the most routes, targets, receptions, yards, touchdowns and end zone targets (17) in the league. He has finished in the top 12 in fantasy PPG in all four of his NFL seasons, including top 5 in three of them. Chase became the league's highest-paid non-quarterback during the offseason and is a heavily targeted 25-year-old superstar on the league's pass-heaviest offense with an elite QB in Joe Burrow. He should be the first WR off the board and is a strong option with the No. 1 overall pick.
